
[1]tolerate

   TOL'ERATE, v.t. [L. tolero, from tollo, to lift.] To suffer to be or to
   be done without prohibition or hinderance; to allow or permit
   negatively, by not preventing; not to restrain; as, to tolerate
   opinions or practices. The protestant religion is tolerated in France,
   and the Roman Catholic in Great Britain.

   Crying should not be tolerated in children.

   The law of love tolerates no vice, and patronizes every virtue.
